post_text:
By now, most of you should have received your school calendar in the mail. Many events listed will shift or look different this year because of COVID-19, although we hope to keep the school breaks the same. There is one big change off the bat, though, and that's our first day of school. We've added two Superintendent Conference Days on Sept. 8 & 9 to give our teachers more time to prepare. That means the first day of school will shift, and it will be different depending on what building and/or cohort your child is in. At elementary, students will start the 10th or 11th, depending on last name. At secondary, one cohort will start the 10th, with the second starting the 14th ‚Äî you'll get more details from your building principal, or you can find them at www.genevacsd.org/reopen.times.

Thank you all for bearing with us through the changes and challenges we face! #inthistogether #genevacsd

post_text:
Hey! What are you doing this summer? The Environmental Studies Summer Youth Institute (ESSYI) at Hobart and William Smith Colleges is offering four full $3,000 scholarships to students at Geneva High!

ESSYI is a two-week summer program for high school students and recent graduates (age 16+) from July 12 ‚Äì July 25. The program introduces students to environmental issues and techniques for addressing environmental problems. This year, it will be facilitated remotely.

Interested students should apply online at essy.hws.edu ‚Äì be sure to indicate your interest in the ‚ÄúGeneva High School Scholarship‚Äù in response to the question regarding where you learned about the program.

Tag a student (or their parent/guardian) you think might be interested!

post_text:
A Message from Superintendent Newton & Board President Canario:

It has come to the Geneva City School District‚Äôs attention that there are petitions circulating on change.org with regards to our school resource officer: One of these petitions advocates cutting the position, while the other advocates keeping it. Although we understand that this is an emotionally charged conversation at the national level, we would like to emphasize that our school resource officer, Raul Arroyo, is an invaluable member of our GCSD family.

All of the SROs we have worked with in Geneva have been excellent. Officer Arroyo is a kind, caring and compassionate individual who is seen by many of our staff and students as a friend and mentor, as evidenced by the number of them who have signed the petition to keep him in our schools. It is a stance we strongly support.

The decision to have an SRO is complex and should lead to a nuanced discussion in each community. What is right for Geneva may not be right elsewhere.

post_text:
The Geneva City School District will livestream graduation on Friday, June 26 from 6:15 p.m.

The Class of 2020 will graduate in a student-only ceremony at Loman Stadium. Parents will be allowed to join a drive-by parade behind the high school at 6:15 p.m., when they can wave to their graduates before the ceremony. The graduation ceremony is expected to begin at 7:30 p.m. The ceremony will include speeches by the high school principal, class president, valedictorian and salutatorian, and the conferring of diplomas.

The livestream will be available on the district‚Äôs website and YouTube channel. Additionally, the ceremony will be broadcast on WHWS radio at Hobart and William Smith Colleges, which can be heard over the air at 105.7fm or online at whws.fm.

More information is available at www.genevacsd.org/2020.

post_text:
The Geneva City School District proposed budget passed with nearly 70 percent voter approval. Candidate Brian Finnerty won election to one five-year term on the school board.

All other propositions also passed. Voters approved the bus purchase, proposition 2, with over 64 percent in favor. The creation of a bus reserve was approved with nearly 62 percent in favor.

The library budget was approved with over 61 percent in favor.

PROPOSITION # 1: ADOPTION OF ANNUAL BUDGET
Yes: 1910
No: 832

PROPOSITION #2: BUS ACQUISITION
Yes: 1736
No: 961

PROPOSITION #3: AUTHORIZATION OF ESTABLISHMENT OF A TRANSPORTATION VEHICLE RESERVE FUND
Yes: 1675
No: 1046

PROPOSITION #4: PUBLIC LIBRARY VOTE AND ELECTION 2020-2021
Yes: 1684
No: 1061

BOARD OF EDUCATION ELECTION
Fred Brockway: 73
Samuel Cappiello: 146
Sarah Cupelli: 271
Mike Ellis (incumbent): 116
Brian Finnerty: 1623
Antonio Gomez: 295
Shelley Higgins-Corbett: 32
Lisa Pietrocarlo: 86
RJ Rapoza: 129

post_text:
What happens if voters defeat the budget on Tuesday, June 16?

The board of education has three options: (1) put the same budget to a second vote, (2) put a revised budget to a vote, or (3) adopt a contingency budget with a 0 percent tax levy increase. In the event that the budget (revised or not) is defeated a second time, the district must adopt a contingency budget by New York State law.

Find out more at www.genevacsd.org/budget

post_text:
Will the district be laying off employees?

Under the best case scenario, the district will be able to reduce expenditures in 2020‚Äì21 through attrition, not filling open positions, pre-paying expenses in 2019‚Äì20 and reducing spending. Our current budget calls for the reduction of 10 positions (nine by attrition, with the 10th an unfilled vacancy).

Find out more at www.genevacsd.org/budget

post_text:
Will COVID-19 impact expenses?

It is expected that COVID-19 mandates/guidelines will result in increased expenses. These expenses are due to a variety of new practices and procedures necessitated by new state laws, executive orders, and health department directives such as increased cleaning/sanitizing and social distancing in school buildings and buses. As an example, the district spends approximately $3,000 on the annual budget vote for supplies and poll workers. This year we are mandated by New York State to do the entire vote through absentee ballots. The cost is estimated to be about $40,000.

The biggest factor impacting the budget is the amount of uncertainty related to revenues and complying with COVID-19 mandates/guidelines. We will all have to adapt as we go through this process together. You can be assured that the district will continue to communicate what we know and don‚Äôt know in order to help you navigate the impacts to the Geneva CSD community.

Find out more at www.genevacsd.org/budget

post_text:
In 10 days, on June 9, 2020, our poll workers will begin opening and counting your absentee ballots. We thought we'd spend the next 10 days answering 10 key questions about the budget. You can find all our FAQs and more at www.genevacsd.org/budget

Question 1/10: What are the primary drivers in the 4.3% increase to the overall budget?

The district‚Äôs cost of out-of-district special education placements has increased over the last five years from $3.96 million to $7.39 million. Each year, the actual expenditures have consistently been greater than projections. Due to the five-year trend, we determined it would be prudent budgeting to add $1.4 million to the budget to accommodate these costs.

post_text:
Gov. Andrew Cuomo has declared that school board elections and budget votes statewide will be held by absentee ballot June 9, 2020. All qualified voters will be sent an absentee ballot with return postage paid. Additionally, school board candidates no longer need signatures to run, although they must be at least 18 and live in the district.

We have one school board seat open for election. Nominations are due to our school board clerk, Adrianne Miller (admiller@genevacsd.org) on May 11, 2020.

We have one school board seat open for election. Nominations are due to our school board clerk, Adrianne Miller (admiller@genevacsd.org) on May 11, 2020.

Please remember that our buildings and grounds (including playgrounds and athletic fields) are currently closed to all but authorized personnel, and dogs are not allowed on the property at any time. Take care and stay healthy!

post_text:
A letter to the Community from the GCSD Board of Education:

We are truly moved by the efforts of people across Geneva to help each other through this confusing period. We are so proud to be a part of this community and to represent you on the Board of Education.

As you know, we have been preparing for and conducting a search for a new superintendent this year. We were thrilled to get so much school and community feedback on our survey over winter break ‚Äî over 500 responses! Thank you. You helped us set the direction for what Geneva needs and deserves from our educational leader.

Read the full letter at www.genevacsd.org/supersearch

Registration for Geneva Little League has been extended until April 12. Parents can register their players at genevalittleleague.com.

Although the fields are currently closed and the start of the season will be delayed until state and local health officials give the OK, the Geneva Little League Board of Directors is still moving ahead with plans for a fun 2020 season, even if it‚Äôs down the road a ways. Like you, they are also eager to hear the words, ‚ÄúPlay ball!‚Äù

Boys and girls from ages 5 to 16 are eligible to play. Parents who need to pay with cash can email genevalittleleagueny@gmail.com to make arrangements.

post_text:
The Geneva City School District will be closed to students on Monday, March 16 because of the state of emergency declared this evening by Ontario County in connection with coronavirus, or COVID-19. All extracurricular and sporting events are canceled, effective immediately.

We will, however, reopen temporarily to students on Tuesday, March 17. Tuesday will be a half day for students throughout the district, with the busing schedule following that of a typical half day. This will allow them to collect any personal items and receive additional information regarding remote learning. At this time, we are unaware of any confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Ontario County.

Following Tuesday morning, the district will be closed until April 14. Please monitor our website, www.genevacsd.org, for updates.

This is uncharted territory for our community and our nation. Thank you for supporting us and each other.

Please refer to our website for the most up-to-date information from us in these rapidly changing circumstances: www.genevacsd.org/coronavirus.

We expect to update families on Monday, March 16.

post_text:
Do you know any available grandparents?

Wayne County Action Program is looking to fill a 20-hour per week volunteer foster grandparent opening at North Street School. The successful candidate will be given mileage at .58 per mile to and from home and receive a stipend of $2.65 per hour completely non-taxable. They also have paid leave time for appointments and 10 sick days per school year, as well as bad weather days.

If anyone knows anyone who currently helps out in one of our school that would be ideal, as they are already part of the school community. Volunteer grandparents provide support to students and teachers throughout Ontario, Seneca, Wayne and Yates counties. This is a great opportunity for retirees seeking a way to give back! For details, email gregory.peck@waynecap.org

post_text:
Be a Geneva Hero!

Geneva Heroes is a program run by Hobart and William Smith students for Geneva students in 7th to 12 grade that focuses on volunteering in the community and building strong relationships along the way.

Each Saturday morning through February and March, Geneva Middle and High School students are welcomed by college students at HWS, and the entire group heads out to different volunteer sites to support our local community together. Lunch is included in the morning.

This is a great opportunity for everyone involved!

So go to your counseling office now and pick up an application today! We must have all applications back by tomorrow, Thursday, January 30--so HURRY and become a Geneva Hero today!

For more information, email Sellers@hws.edu.
